AP Environmental Science — Unit 1: The Living World: Ecosystems

Q1. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S7Q1)
Which of the following processes is primarily responsible for transferring carbon from the atmosphere to the terrestrial biosphere?
  • A. Photosynthesis
  • B. Respiration
  • C. Combustion
  • D. Decomposition
Q2. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S7Q2)
If the producers in an ecosystem contain $10,000$ kcal of energy, approximately how much energy would be available to the secondary consumers?
  • A. $1,000$ kcal
  • B. $100$ kcal
  • C. $10$ kcal
  • D. $1$ kcal
Q3. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S7Q3)
Which of the following describes the role of denitrification in the nitrogen cycle?
  • A. Conversion of atmospheric nitrogen gas into ammonia
  • B. Assimilation of nitrates by plants for growth
  • C. Conversion of ammonia into nitrites and then nitrates
  • D. Conversion of nitrates back into atmospheric nitrogen gas
Q4. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S7Q4)
A food web shows a grasshopper eating grass, a frog eating the grasshopper, a snake eating the frog, and a hawk eating the snake. A fox eats both grasshoppers and frogs. If a pesticide significantly reduces the grasshopper population, which of the following is the most likely initial effect on the other populations?
  • A. The hawk population would increase.
  • B. The frog population would increase.
  • C. The snake population would decrease.
  • D. The fox population would increase.
Q5. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S7Q5)
Which of the following terrestrial biomes is characterized by permafrost, low biodiversity, and a short growing season?
  • A. Tundra
  • B. Taiga
  • C. Temperate rainforest
  • D. Tropical seasonal forest
Q6. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S7Q6)
Which of the following is a primary way that phosphorus is introduced into aquatic ecosystems from terrestrial sources?
  • A. Atmospheric deposition
  • B. Runoff from agricultural fields
  • C. Denitrification by bacteria
  • D. Evaporation from land
Q7. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S7Q7)
Which of the following statements best describes the role of producers in an ecosystem?
  • A. They consume other organisms for energy.
  • B. They break down dead organic matter.
  • C. They convert solar energy into chemical energy.
  • D. They regulate nutrient cycling in the soil.
Q8. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S7Q8)
Which zone of an aquatic biome is characterized by low light penetration, low oxygen levels, and decomposers?
  • A. Littoral zone
  • B. Benthic zone
  • C. Photic zone
  • D. Limnetic zone
Q9. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S7Q9)
Which of the following describes a mutualistic relationship between two species?
  • A. A tick feeding on a deer
  • B. A lion preying on a zebra
  • C. A bee pollinating a flower
  • D. Two species of birds competing for the same nesting site
Q10. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S7Q10)
In a typical food chain, what percentage of energy is typically transferred from one trophic level to the next?
  • A. $1\%$
  • B. $10\%$
  • C. $50\%$
  • D. $90\%$
Q11. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S7Q11)
If a tertiary consumer requires $200$ kcal of energy per day, and assuming a $10\%$ energy transfer efficiency between trophic levels, how much producer energy would be needed to sustain this consumer for one day?
  • A. $200,000$ kcal
  • B. $20,000$ kcal
  • C. $2,000$ kcal
  • D. $20$ kcal
Q12. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S7Q12)
Which of the following processes in the hydrologic cycle is responsible for the direct return of water vapor from plants to the atmosphere?
  • A. Precipitation
  • B. Evaporation
  • C. Condensation
  • D. Transpiration
Q13. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S7Q13)

  • A. Deforestation
  • B. Agriculture
  • C. Dam construction
  • D. Water purification
Q14. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S7Q14)
Which of the following biomes is characterized by warm temperatures year-round, high rainfall, and very high biodiversity?
  • A. Taiga
  • B. Tropical rainforest
  • C. Temperate grassland
  • D. Desert
Q15. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S7Q15)
Human activities, such as the use of synthetic fertilizers, have significantly altered the nitrogen cycle. What is a major environmental consequence of this alteration?
  • A. Increased atmospheric nitrogen gas levels
  • B. Decreased soil fertility
  • C. Reduced primary productivity in terrestrial ecosystems
  • D. Eutrophication of aquatic ecosystems
Q16. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S7Q16)
Gross Primary Productivity (GPP) refers to the total amount of energy captured by producers. Which of the following is the best definition of Net Primary Productivity (NPP)?
  • A. The energy remaining after cellular respiration by producers
  • B. The energy transferred to the next trophic level
  • C. The total energy available from consumers
  • D. The energy lost as heat during photosynthesis
Q17. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S7Q17)
Unlike the carbon and nitrogen cycles, the phosphorus cycle does not have a significant atmospheric gaseous phase. Where is the largest reservoir of phosphorus typically found?
  • A. Sedimentary rock
  • B. Atmosphere
  • C. Oceans (dissolved)
  • D. Living organisms
Q18. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S7Q18)
Which of the following is the best example of a keystone species?
  • A. A species with a very large population size.
  • B. A species that is a primary producer in its ecosystem.
  • C. A species whose removal has a disproportionately large effect on its ecosystem.
  • D. A species that is highly specialized to a particular niche.
Q19. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S7Q19)
A grassland ecosystem has $5,000$ kg of biomass at the producer level. If the energy transfer efficiency is $10\%$, how much biomass can be supported at the primary consumer level?
  • A. $50,000$ kg
  • B. $500$ kg
  • C. $50$ kg
  • D. $5$ kg

  • C. Oceans
  • D. Cellular respiration
